Peel and slice the @onion{1} in half lengthways through the root. Turn your onion 
widthways and slice it very thinly into half moon shapes. Peel and finely chop 
the @garlic cloves{4}. Chop the @new potatoes{2} and the @cherry plum tomatoes{2} 
in half and very, very finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}.

Add a splash of @olive oil{} to a #pan{} on medium heat. Add your onion and garlic 
with a pinch of @salt{}. Gently cook for ~{10%minutes}. We don't want to colour 
the onion, so if it begins to brown, add a splash of @water{} and turn the heat 
down a little.

Meanwhile, on medium-high heat, bring a medium-sized #pot{} of water with a pinch 
of salt, to the boil.

Add your new potatoes to the pot and boil for around ~{12-15%minutes}.

> Tip: Your potatoes are done when you can easily slip a knife a knife 
  through them.

When cooked, drain them and keep to the side.

When your onion and garlic have been cooking for ~{10%minutes}, add your cherry 
tomatoes to the pan and keep cooking for another ~{10%minutes}. The mixture 
should start to bubble and your tomatoes will soften.

Heat another splash of @olive oil{} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium-high 
heat. Once the oil is very hot, sprinkle a little @salt{} on both sides of the 
@sea bream fillets{4} and lay gently in the pan skin-side down. Cook for 
~{3%minutes} without touching. Now gently turn over and cook for another 
~{2%minutes}, before removing from the heat.

Add the @white wine vinegar{2} and a sprinkle of @sugar{} (if you have some) to 
your cherry tomato mixture. Stir and cook for ~{3%minutes} before removing from 
the heat. Stir through half of your parsley.

Serve everything together with your remaining parsley sprinkled on top and get 
stuck in!